# Documentation Standards

## Code Comments

- Add comments in **English** for all public methods and classes
- Explain **why**, not **what** (code should be self-explanatory)
- Document complex algorithms and business logic
- Include parameter descriptions for public methods

## Class Documentation

- Document the purpose of each class
- Explain when and how to use the class
- Document any important assumptions or constraints

Example:
```pascal
  /// <summary>
  /// Handles HTTP requests and routes them to appropriate endpoints
  /// </summary>
  TRequestHandler = class
  end;
```

## Method Documentation

- Document public and protected methods
- Explain parameters and return values
- Note any side effects or exceptions that may be raised
- Include usage examples for complex methods

Example:
```pascal
  /// <summary>
  /// Processes user authentication request
  /// </summary>
  /// <param name="username">User login name</param>
  /// <param name="password">User password</param>
  /// <returns>Authentication token if successful, empty string otherwise</returns>
  function AuthenticateUser(const username, password: string): string;
```

## Unit Documentation

- Add unit-level comments explaining the purpose
- Document dependencies and relationships with other units
- Note any global state or initialization requirements

## README and Project Documentation

- Keep README.md up to date
- Document setup instructions
- Explain project structure
- Include examples of common operations
